= Service-Driven Approach (SDA) to workflow management

To illustrate the structured framework applied to the eProcurement Ontology (ePO) lifecycle, the Service-Driven Approach (SDA) provides a clear, layered view that shows how each level of the enterprise architecture supports workflow management. This approach uses a layered "stack" in ArchiMate, with business aspects at the top, application functions in the middle, and technology infrastructure at the bottom. By connecting layers through services, the SDA approach enables a cohesive view of dependencies and support relationships across Business, Application, and Technology layers.

_Layered view  http://www.hosiaisluoma.fi/ArchiMate-Cookbook.pdf[Basic Archimate design Patern]_

The diagram above captures this layered structure, illustrating how each layer in the SDA model builds on the one below it to fulfil the ePOs workflow requirements. Below is a summary of each layers role and function within this structure:

. *External Roles and Actors*: The top layer represents external stakeholders, such as customers or partners who engage with the organisation. These actors are assigned specific roles, which define how they interact with the organisations services.
. *Business Services*: This layer defines the services provided to external actors. These services are central to the organisations value delivery and form the interface through which it interacts with customers or other stakeholders.
. *Processes and Internal Roles and Actors*: Internal business processes, supported by assigned roles, are captured here. These processes fulfil the business services and interact with data or documents needed to achieve specific outcomes.
. *Application Services*: This layer contains the application servicessuch as user interfaces (GUIs) or APIsthat support and enhance the organisations business processes by providing essential software functionality.
. *Applications and Data*: Applications at this layer realise application services, interacting with specific data objects (datasets or documents) that they manage or process in support of the business processes.
. *Technology and Infrastructure Services*: Foundational technology services, such as networking or capacity management, reside here. These services ensure the operational stability and reliability of applications within the enterprise.
. *Infrastructure / Platforms*: The base layer includes the physical infrastructureservers, networks, and other devicesthat hosts and executes applications and services. This infrastructure accesses and maintains various artifacts, such as executables and configuration files, that are essential for the stable operation of the system.
Each layer in this service-driven model is interconnected, creating a fully integrated workflow that aligns with the ePO's objectives. The SDA framework clarifies both top-down dependencies (business requirements driving technology support) and bottom-up dependencies (technology enabling business processes), providing a complete view of the ePOs architecture. This approach enables robust governance, aligns IT with business goals, and provides a clear path for decision-making and traceability across the ePO lifecycle.
